<TITLE> Clamour grows for Beckham to stay at AC Milan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MILAN, Jan 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - David Beckham scored his first goal for AC Milan in a 4-1 Serie A win at Bologna on Sunday but coach Carlo Ancelotti played down speculation the England midfielder could stay at the club. The 33-year-old, on loan from Los Angeles Galaxy for two months, finished off a fine move by blasting in at the near post to complete the scoring on 59 minutes. Beckham has impressed Italian fans and pundits in his three league outings for Milan, playing simple passes and making very few errors. He joined the Rossoneri to stay in the England reckoning during the U.S. close season and has consistently said he will stick to the agreement and return to Los Angeles on March 9. "Our hands are tied because he has a clear contract," Ancelotti, who was celebrating his 400th match as Milan coach, told reporters. "We can't do anything to change things, he can definitely do something. He must sort out his contract with the American team. I am a realist, we will take advantage of him for now." Italian media quoted Beckham as saying "We will see" when asked after the game about the prospect of staying at Milan beyond the end of the loan. It was a good day all-round for third-placed Milan with Brazilian playmaker Kaka, whose world record move to Manchester City fell through last week, scoring with a penalty and with a superb shot from the edge of the box. On-loan Arsenal defender Philippe Senderos made his first Serie A start after injury but Ronaldinho began on the bench after recent lacklustre display
